No, no, no.  I'm saying that crime pays in the long run when done right.

Egoism has a very strict definition: "An action is right if and only if it
maximizes the total long-term utility of the agent." Choosing a principle
is an action, too; if following a principle ever results in less long run
utility for the agent than rejecting that principle, then the principle is
wrong from the perspective of egoism. 

While choosing principles does happen to be rational, it is because egoism
is not rational, not because egoism demands it.  Indeed, egoism demands
that we reject the principle whenever principled behavior would result in
suboptimal agent utility.

> I also consider crime opposed to
